Solution: Long Hunt (picoCTF)
In this challenge, I was provided with a large server.log file containing a vast amount of data. My goal was to filter through the logs to extract the hidden flag.

1. Initial Reconnaissance
To understand the structure of the log file, I first used the following command to see general information:
cat server.log | grep INFO

2. Identifying the Flag Pattern
Upon inspection, I discovered that the fragments of the password (flag) were labeled with the keyword FLAGPART. To isolate these specific lines, I refined my search:
cat server.log | grep FLAGPART

3. Data Cleaning and Deduplication
The output contained many duplicate entries, making it difficult to reconstruct the flag. I used the uniq command to remove these duplicates. However, I learned an important rule: uniq only detects duplicate lines that are adjacent. To ensure uniq works correctly, the data must be ordered first. Therefore, I piped the output through sort before deduplicating.

Final Optimized Command:
cat server.log | grep FLAGPART | sort | uniq

By sorting the lines alphabetically, identical "FLAGPART" entries were grouped together, allowing uniq to efficiently filter them out. I then combined the remaining unique parts to form the final flag.

